# Visual CMS and design tools for a self-hosted Next.js stack

**The short answer to your core question:** No single Mac desktop app lets you visually drag-and-drop edit a Next.js + Tailwind + shadcn/ui site and push changes live. Your best workflow is **Cursor (Mac app) + Claude Code (terminal) + your browser side-by-side** — describe changes to Claude Code in plain English, watch them appear on your live site via hot reload. For structured content editing (blog posts, council documents, motions), **Payload CMS v3's admin panel at `/admin`** is your visual interface. Below is the complete guide for both topics.

---

## Topic 1: Migrating to Payload CMS v3 — complete step-by-step

### Installing Payload into an existing Next.js 15 project

Payload CMS v3 is now at **version 3.82.1** (April 2026). Figma acquired Payload in June 2025, but development continues with weekly releases. Payload v3 runs embedded inside Next.js — it is not a separate server. Your Next.js app and CMS share one process, one deployment, one URL.

**Step 1 — Install packages:**

```bash
pnpm add payload @payloadcms/next @payloadcms/richtext-lexical @payloadcms/db-postgres sharp graphql
```

All `@payloadcms/*` packages must be the same version. The PostgreSQL adapter (`@payloadcms/db-postgres`) uses Drizzle ORM internally — you do not install Drizzle separately.

**Step 2 — Environment variables** (add to `.env`):

```env
DATABASE_URI="postgres://user:password@localhost:5432/your_database"
PAYLOAD_SECRET="generate-with-openssl-rand-base64-32"
NEXT_PUBLIC_SERVER_URL="https://yourdomain.com"
```

**Step 3 — Create `payload.config.ts`** at your project root (or `src/payload.config.ts`):

```typescript
import sharp from 'sharp'
import { lexicalEditor } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical'
import { postgresAdapter } from '@payloadcms/db-postgres'
import { buildConfig } from 'payload'
import { Users } from './src/collections/Users'
import { Pages } from './src/collections/Pages'
import { Media } from './src/collections/Media'

export default buildConfig({
  editor: lexicalEditor(),
  collections: [Users, Pages, Media],
  secret: process.env.PAYLOAD_SECRET || '',
  db: postgresAdapter({
    pool: { connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URI || '' },
  }),
  sharp,
  admin: {
    user: 'users',
    meta: { titleSuffix: '- Civic Tech CMS' },
  },
  typescript: {
    outputFile: 'src/payload-types.ts',
  },
})
```

**Step 4 — Add path alias** to `tsconfig.json`:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "paths": {
      "@payload-config": ["./payload.config.ts"]
    }
  }
}
```

**Step 5 — Wrap your Next.js config** (`next.config.mjs`):

```javascript
import { withPayload } from '@payloadcms/next/withPayload'

const nextConfig = {
  // your existing config
  output: 'standalone', // required for Docker
}

export default withPayload(nextConfig)
```

Your config file must use ESM format (`.mjs` extension or `"type": "module"` in `package.json`).

**Step 6 — Create the (payload) route group.** This is the critical step. Copy the route group structure from [Payload's blank template](https://github.com/payloadcms/payload/tree/main/templates/blank/src/app/(payload)) into your `app/` directory:

```
app/
├── (payload)/                      ← Payload admin + API
│   ├── admin/
│   │   └── [[...segments]]/
│   │       ├── page.tsx            ← Admin panel pages
│   │       └── not-found.tsx
│   ├── api/
│   │   └── [...slug]/
│   │       └── route.ts           ← REST API
│   ├── graphql/
│   │   └── route.ts
│   ├── custom.scss
│   └── layout.tsx                 ← Payload root layout
├── (frontend)/                     ← YOUR existing app (renamed)
│   ├── layout.tsx                 ← Your original root layout
│   ├── page.tsx
│   └── ...all your existing routes
```

Move all your existing app files into a `(frontend)` route group. Parenthesized folder names don't appear in URLs — your pages keep their existing paths.

The key files inside `(payload)` import from `@payloadcms/next` and should not be modified. Here is the admin page file:

```tsx
// app/(payload)/admin/[[...segments]]/page.tsx
import config from '@payload-config'
import { RootPage, generatePageMetadata } from '@payloadcms/next/views'
import { importMap } from '../importMap'

type Args = {
  params: Promise<{ segments: string[] }>
  searchParams: Promise<{ [key: string]: string | string[] }>
}

export const generateMetadata = ({ params, searchParams }: Args) =>
  generatePageMetadata({ config, params, searchParams })

const Page = ({ params, searchParams }: Args) =>
  RootPage({ config, importMap, params, searchParams })

export default Page
```

**Step 7 — Start dev and create your first user:**

```bash
pnpm dev
```

Navigate to `http://localhost:3000/admin`. Payload prompts you to create the first admin user. The admin panel, REST API (`/api/[collection]`), and your frontend all run on the same Next.js server.

### PostgreSQL and Drizzle ORM configuration

The adapter handles everything. In development, **push mode** is enabled by default — Payload auto-syncs your schema changes to the database using Drizzle's `db push`. For production, use migrations:

```bash
pnpm payload migrate:create --name initial_schema  # generates migration file
pnpm payload migrate                                # runs pending migrations
```

You can access the underlying Drizzle client directly for custom queries:

```typescript
const payload = await getPayload({ config })
const db = payload.db.drizzle        // full Drizzle client
const tables = payload.db.tables     // all table definitions
```

Import Drizzle utilities from the adapter:

```typescript
import { eq, and } from '@payloadcms/db-postgres/drizzle'
```

