## Topic 2: Mac desktop apps for visual web design

### The honest answer to your core question

**"Which Mac application do I open when I want to visually design and edit my website's pages, and have those changes appear on my live self-hosted site?"**

Unlike WordPress or Squarespace, a Next.js + Payload CMS + Tailwind + shadcn/ui stack is a **code-first architecture**. No single Mac desktop app provides a Squarespace-like visual editor that directly edits and deploys a Next.js project. Your visual editing interface is a combination of: **Payload CMS admin panel** (for content), **Claude Code** (for layout and design changes via natural language), and **your browser** (for seeing the result). Below is the detailed analysis of every tool you asked about.

### Tools that can directly edit Next.js project files

Only a handful of tools can open and meaningfully edit `.tsx` files in a Next.js project:

**Cursor** ($20/month Pro) is the strongest recommendation for your workflow. It is a VS Code fork with deep AI integration that complements Claude Code perfectly. Connect to your Hetzner server via Remote SSH, edit files with full Tailwind CSS IntelliSense, and use Cursor's AI for quick inline fixes while using Claude Code for larger architectural changes. **Both tools can work on the same project simultaneously.** Cursor sees code, not rendered pages — you still view your site in a browser. The free Hobby tier provides 2,000 completions/month and 50 slow premium requests.

**VS Code** (free) provides the same core file-editing capabilities as Cursor, with the official Tailwind CSS IntelliSense extension for autocomplete and hover previews. Remote SSH editing works excellently. Cursor is recommended over VS Code for this use case because it includes all VS Code functionality plus AI assistance, but if cost is a concern, VS Code is a strong free alternative.

**Nova by Panic** ($99 first year, $49/year renewal) is a Mac-native code editor with **best-in-class built-in SSH/SFTP** support — you can browse, edit, and auto-upload files to your Hetzner server on save. It has native JSX/TSX syntax support and a Tailwind CSS extension for completions. However, it is purely a code editor with a preview pane — no visual design capabilities, no AI coding assistance, and a much smaller extension ecosystem than VS Code. Choose Nova only if you strongly value native Mac design and built-in SFTP over AI features.

**WebStorm** (free for non-commercial use, $149/year commercial) offers excellent built-in Tailwind CSS v4 support and remote development via JetBrains Gateway. It provides zero visual/WYSIWYG editing. Its advanced refactoring tools are largely redundant when Claude Code handles your development. Not recommended for this use case.

### Tools that produce separate output requiring manual integration

**Figma** (free tier available, Pro at $12/month) is the industry-standard design tool. It cannot edit your codebase — it produces visual mockups that must be converted to code. The Figma-to-code pipeline has improved significantly:

- **Anima** ($24/seat/month) generates React + Tailwind CSS code from Figma designs with clean, readable output
- **Locofy** ($33-100/month) outputs Next.js components with Tailwind and file-based routing
- **Builder.io Visual Copilot** converts Figma designs to React/Next.js code in one click
- **Figma Dev Mode** provides CSS inspection, measurements, and now integrates with AI coding agents via MCP server

For a solo non-developer using Claude Code, the Figma workflow adds complexity: design → export → paste into project → refine. A more efficient approach is describing what you want directly to Claude Code. Figma is useful if you think visually and want to mock up layouts before building, but it is an extra step, not a direct pipeline.

**Sketch** ($120 one-time Mac license) has limited code export capabilities compared to Figma — only a theme-token-to-Tailwind-config plugin exists. No direct React code generation. Figma has comprehensively won the design tool market for developer workflows, and Sketch's smaller plugin ecosystem makes it the inferior choice for this stack. Not recommended.

### Tools that cannot work with Next.js at all

**Pinegrow Web Editor** ($12/month desktop app) has excellent Tailwind CSS visual editing — but only for static HTML files. It cannot open or understand React/JSX/TSX files. However, **Piny**, Pinegrow's newer VS Code/Cursor extension (launched 2025, free tier available), can visually edit Tailwind classes directly in JSX/TSX files within your IDE. This is the closest thing to a visual Tailwind editor that works with actual React code. It is still new and maturing but worth watching.

**RapidWeaver Elements** (~$119) builds standalone websites using Tailwind CSS internally and publishes via FTP/SFTP. It produces its own HTML structure and cannot open, read, or interact with an existing Next.js project in any way. Not suitable.

**Blocs** ($113-$180 one-time) produces static Bootstrap-based HTML websites. Uses Bootstrap, not Tailwind. Cannot work with existing codebases. Wrong framework, wrong output format. Not suitable.

**Whisk** (inexpensive, by Tumult) is a minimally maintained lightweight HTML editor with live preview. No JSX/TSX awareness, no Tailwind support, no remote connectivity. Vastly inferior to VS Code. Not suitable.

**Tumult Hype** ($50-$100 one-time) creates HTML5 animations with a timeline editor. Its output is standalone HTML/CSS/JS bundles that have no relationship to React components, Tailwind CSS, or modern frameworks. Only useful if you need a specific standalone animation embedded via iframe. Not suitable for page design.

### Builder.io as a visual page editor alongside Payload CMS

**Builder.io** (free tier, paid from ~$19/month) is the only tool that genuinely answers your core question — it provides a **drag-and-drop visual page builder** on top of your existing Next.js project. You register your React/shadcn components with Builder.io, and then anyone can compose pages visually in a browser-based editor. Published changes appear on your live site automatically.

It can coexist with Payload CMS: **Payload manages structured data** (council documents, motions, blog posts) while **Builder.io manages visual page layouts** (homepage, landing pages, marketing content). However, running two CMSs adds significant complexity — two systems to learn, two content sources to manage, and an external dependency for page content. For a solo operator, this is likely overkill when Payload's block-based page builder already provides substantial flexibility for page composition.

Builder.io is entirely web-based — there is no Mac desktop app. You access it through your browser.

