### The definitive recommendation for your setup

Your daily workflow should involve **three windows**:

1. **Your browser** open to `https://yourdomain.com/admin` — this is Payload CMS's admin panel where you create and edit content (pages, posts, council documents, motions, investigations) using the block-based page builder with live preview. This is your primary "visual" content editing tool. No code required.

2. **Your browser** open to `https://yourdomain.com` — your live site, showing the result of your changes in real time via hot module replacement during development.

3. **Cursor** (Mac app, $20/month) connected via SSH to your Hetzner server, with **Claude Code running in its integrated terminal**. When you want to change how something *looks* (layout, design, components, styling), describe it to Claude Code: *"Make the hero section background a gradient from blue to purple, increase the heading font size, and add a shadow to the CTA button."* Claude Code edits the actual Tailwind/shadcn/React files. Your browser refreshes automatically.

This three-window setup gives you: structured content management without code (Payload admin), natural-language design changes (Claude Code), visual code review and small tweaks (Cursor), and instant visual feedback (browser). **No additional Mac desktop application is needed.** The traditional visual web design tools (Pinegrow, RapidWeaver, Blocs) were built for a pre-React, pre-component world and cannot meaningfully interact with a modern Next.js stack. The AI-powered workflow of Claude Code + Payload CMS replaces what those tools used to provide — and does it better for your specific setup.

## Conclusion

Payload CMS v3 embedded in Next.js transforms your server into a full content management platform with a clean admin panel, block-based page building, draft/publish workflow, and live preview — all running in a single Docker container on your Hetzner CCX33. The civic tech collections (council documents, motions, investigations) map naturally to Payload's relational collection model, and hooks provide seamless integration with your FastAPI backend for RAG enrichment and data syncing.

The Mac desktop visual design tool landscape reveals a fundamental truth: **the era of visual-editor-to-live-site tools ended with the shift to component-based frameworks**. No desktop app in 2026 provides a Squarespace-like experience for a Next.js codebase. The modern equivalent is your CMS admin panel (Payload) for content, plus an AI coding assistant (Claude Code) for design — which is actually more powerful, since you can describe any visual change in words rather than being constrained by a drag-and-drop interface's built-in options. Piny (Pinegrow's VS Code extension for visual Tailwind editing in JSX) is the most promising emerging tool to watch for bridging this gap, but the Claude Code + Cursor + Payload admin workflow is the most practical and capable approach available today.